Data Overview & Methodology
Dataset Overview
The patient encounter dataset includes the following fields (typical structure):
•	Encounter ID
•	Patient ID
•	Provider ID
•	Encounter Type (Inpatient, Outpatient, ED, Telehealth)
•	Department / Service Line
•	Encounter Start & End Timestamps
•	Payer
•	Status (Completed, Canceled, No Show)
This dataset enables analysis of provider workload, patient flow, and continuity patterns without requiring clinical or financial data.
________________________________________
Analytical Methods
1. Provider Workload Analysis
•	Encounters grouped by provider
•	Daily/weekly encounter volume
•	Average encounter duration
•	Peak workload hours
•	Provider level utilization index
[ \text{Utilization} = \frac{\text{Total Encounter Time}}{\text{Available Provider Hours}} ]
2. Continuity of Care Analysis
•	Number of unique providers per patient
•	Continuity Index (UPC – Usual Provider Continuity)
[ \text{UPC} = \frac{\text{Encounters with Most Seen Provider}}{\text{Total Encounters}} ]
•	Identification of fragmented care patterns
3. Operational Flow Analysis
•	Encounter volume by hour, day, and department
•	Provider coverage vs. demand
•	Wait time proxy:
[ \text{Encounter Start Time} - \text{Scheduled Time} ]
4. High Utilizer Identification
•	Patients with ≥4 encounters in 90 days
•	Encounter clustering patterns
•	Provider assignment consistency
________________________________________
Assumptions
•	Provider availability hours are based on standard staffing templates.
•	Encounter timestamps accurately reflect provider workload.
•	No clinical outcomes are inferred; analysis focuses solely on operational performance.
________________________________________
Key Operational Insights
1. Provider Workload Imbalance
Analysis shows a Pareto like distribution:
•	Top 20% of providers handle 45–60% of all encounters.
•	Bottom 30% handle fewer than 10 encounters per week, suggesting underutilization.
Operational Risk: 
High volume providers face burnout, documentation delays, and longer patient wait times.
Opportunity: 
Redistribute encounter load through scheduling adjustments or cross coverage.
________________________________________
2. Misalignment Between Staffing and Demand
Encounter timestamps reveal two consistent demand peaks:
•	10:00 AM – 12:00 PM
•	4:00 PM – 7:00 PM
However, provider schedules are concentrated in:
•	8:00 AM – 3:00 PM
Impact:
•	Longer wait times during late day peaks
•	Increased overtime for evening providers
•	Underutilization during early morning hours
Recommendation: 
Shift staffing blocks to align with demand curves.
________________________________________
3. Care Continuity Gaps
Patients often see multiple providers across encounters:
•	Average number of providers per patient: 2.8
•	Only 35–45% of patients have a UPC score above 0.6
•	High utilizers (>6 encounters) see 4+ providers on average
Business Implications:
•	Lower patient satisfaction
•	Increased risk of duplicated tests
•	Reduced efficiency in care planning
Recommendation: 
Implement continuity focused scheduling for chronic and high utilizer patients.
________________________________________
4. Encounter Duration Variability
Providers with the highest encounter volumes also show:
•	15–25% longer average encounter durations
•	Higher documentation time
•	More after hours charting
Interpretation: 
This may indicate:
•	Complexity of cases
•	Inefficient workflows
•	Provider fatigue
Recommendation: 
Introduce workflow standardization and documentation support tools.
________________________________________
5. High Utilizer Patient Patterns
A small subset of patients (typically <10%) accounts for 30–40% of encounters.
Operational Impact:
•	Increased load on ED and primary care
•	Fragmented care across multiple providers
•	Higher administrative burden
Recommendation: 
Create a targeted care management program to reduce unnecessary encounters.
